title: Deaths-in-custody data

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Deaths-in-custody data
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

(1) Records, or an in index of records, of all California law enforcement agencies deaths-in-custody between 1980 and today’s date, including all deaths-in-custody reported pursuant to California Government Code (GC) section 12525.

(2) Records, or an index of records, of any and all California law enforcement agencies’ responses to the California Department of Justice annual survey of the total number of subject deaths per calendar year since 1980 or since the state began gathering such data, including pursuant to California Government Code (GC) section 12525.

I understand that the California Department of Justice maintains part of this data online, including on the Open Justice portal, however, this request is seeking data in a downloadable, .csv-readable format dating back to 1980 or since the state began gathering such data, whichever is greater.

If records pursuant to this request are possessed in machine-readable format such as an .xls or .csv spreadsheet file, please provide the record in this format.

The fundamental rule of the CPRA is a presumption of public access. “In other words, [A]ll public records are subject to disclosure unless the Legislature has expressly provided to the contrary.” Williams v. Superior Court, 5 Cal. 4th 337 (1993). This presumption finds further support in the California Constitution, as amended by Proposition 59 in 2004. “A statute, court rule, or other authority, including those in effect on the effective date of this subdivision, shall be broadly construed if it furthers the people's right of access, and narrowly construed if it limits the right of access.” Cal. Const. Art. 1 § 3(b)(2).

Please provide a determination on this request within 10 days of your receipt of it. If you determine that any or all of the information qualifies for an exemption from disclosure, please note whether, as is normally the case, the exemption is discretionary, and if so whether it is necessary in this case to exercise your discretion to withhold the information. If you determine that some but not all of the information is exempt from disclosure and that you intend to withhold it, please redact it for the time being and make the rest available as requested. In any event, please provide a signed notification citing the legal authorities on which you rely if you determine that any or all of the information is exempt and will not be disclosed.

Please apply a fee waiver to this request. If the request for a fee waiver is denied, please provide notification of any duplication costs exceeding $80 before you duplicate the records. If the request for a fee waiver is denied, please further provide an index of all other requests since 2014 for which a fee waiver was denied, and the reason therefor.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Dillon Bergin

title: Flock Safety search audits, network sharing, and general order (Columbia River Drug Task Force)

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Flock Safety search audits, network sharing, and general order (Columbia River Drug Task Force)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records related to the department’s Flock Safety system:
1. Organization Audit in Flock. 
The report should include data logged from the period of December 1, 2024, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Organization Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches done within the agency.

2. Network Audit in Flock.
The report should include data logged from the period of December 1, 2024, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Network Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches of the organization’s Flock network by any agency in the Flock System.

3. A list of network share settings that include:
3a. Flock networks shared with me
3b. Networks that I’m sharing

Please provide records in their original electronic, machine readable format. For example, please provide csv or spreadsheet files where applicable. Please do not redirect me to your transparency portal.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Rose Terse

communications.subject: RTKL 0625-25 Interim Response
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Sawyer,

This email acknowledges receipt by the Department of Corrections (the Department) of your written request for records under the Pennsylvania Right-to-Know Law (RTKL). Your request was received on June 2, 2025.

title: South Carolina Medical Board

communications.subject: South Carolina Public Records Law Request: South Carolina Medical Board
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the South Carolina Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

I’m conducting national research on how medical boards across the U.S. manage physician mental health and substance use cases—especially in relation to physician health or monitoring programs. A key question is whether such programs operate independently or in concert with disciplinary enforcement.

I respectfully request the following records from the South Carolina Board of Medical Examiners (or LLR) for the period 2019–2024:

1. A list of disciplinary actions involving physicians where:

Psychological or psychiatric impairment was cited

Substance use or behavioral health concerns were involved

2. Board or departmental policies or procedures regarding:

Referrals to the South Carolina Recovering Professional Program (RPP)

Evaluation of return-to-practice after monitoring or treatment

3. Agreements, contracts, or memoranda of understanding between the board and RPP, including:

Confidentiality provisions

Reporting requirements

Criteria for board acceptance or rejection of RPP recommendations

4. Summary statistics or internal reports showing:

Number of referrals to RPP

Voluntary vs. mandated participation

Return-to-practice outcomes

Any cases where the board diverged from RPP recommendations

5. Evaluations or audits (internal or external) assessing RPP’s independence or effectiveness.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Vig Sinclair

title: Fremont PD Dismissed Red Light Camera Tickets [2020-2025]

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Fremont PD Dismissed Red Light Camera Tickets [2020-2025]
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records relating to the number of red light camera tickets that were dismissed by the officer reviewing the footage/photograph captured by the camera starting from January 2020 to December 2025.

The information requested is readily available for extraction through the Redflex System. For example, a records request for similar data fulfilled by the Beverly Hills Police Department of Beverly Hills, CA provided a Customer Management Report generated by the Redflex System. That provided Customer Management Report is attached to this request for reference.

However, should you disagree, you may alternatively produce the following records:

* Number of Potential Violations collected by the Redflex System between the periods of January 2020 to December 2025, preferably segregated by year or month

* Number of Authorized Violations collected by the Redflex System between the periods of January 2020 to December 2025. This may also be the number of Electronic Signatures given by the Authorized Officer using the Redflex

* Monthly reports generated by the Redflex Standard Report System, as mentioned in Section 7.8.2 of the AGREEMENT BETWEEN THE CITY OF FREMONT AND REDFLEX TRAFFIC SYSTEMS, INC. FOR PHOTO RED LIGHT ENFORCEMENT PROGRAM (a copy of this agreement is attached to this request for reference)

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

John Doe

title: Superintendent Travel

communications.subject: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: Superintendent Travel
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Virginia Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

A publicly available VMI Alumni Association publication, "Turnouts", released this week, states that Maj. Gen. Wins received several commendations from them. A trip by the Superintendent to the Republic of China was also mentioned. Therefore, I am requesting:

1. Copies of the commendations, awards, etc., given by the Alumni Agencies and their organizations to Maj. Gen. Wins in his capacity as VMI Superintendent. These are now public documents.

2. Records showing the itinerary, meetings, or other events, agenda, travel, results, and all related information for the Superintendent's trip to the Republic of China, as well as the source of funds to pay for the trip.  The publication stated that he went in his official capacity as Superintendent of VMI and conducted VMI or Joint VMI and Alumni Agencies business, so these records are subject to FOIA, as he is a public employee.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Tom Nash, a citizen of Virginia, in coordination with Anonymous.

communications.subject: RE: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: Superintendent Travel
communications.communication: I also want to add to my FOIA records showing anyone who travelled with the Superintendent to the Republic of China, VMI employee or not, their role, itinerary, etc., and the source of funding for their travel.

title: VMI Admissions Data

communications.subject: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request: VMI Admissions Data
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Virginia Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records for the following academic years showing:

1. The breakout of applicants accepted for admission to VMI (appointments) by race, ethnicity, gender, and within each of those, which were athletes and non-athletes

2. The breakout of new cadets that matriculated to VMI (showed up and enrolled on admissions day) by race, ethnicity, gender, and within each of those, which were athletes and non-athletes.

3. The number and dollar value of each scholarship or tuition assistance from cadets by race, ethnicity, gender, and within each of those, which were athletes and non-athletes, with the source of funding (e.g., VMI Agencies, Federal Government, VMI internal funds, other).

Academic years covered:

2015 - 2016
2016 - 2017
2017 - 2018
2018 - 2019
2019 - 2020
2020 - 2021
2021 - 2022
2022 - 2023
2023 - 2024
2024 - 2025

This information is known to be a reporting requirement for various state and federal agencies, and, in the past, some, if not all, was available in the VMI Data Dashboard that has since been closed. Therefore, this information should be readily available in that,a dn tother readily available systems and systems of systems to be provided.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

communications.subject: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Police department misconduct allegations and disciplinary proceedings
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

All materials and records describing and sufficient to show/disclose all allegations of misconduct made and all disciplinary proceedings taken against any officer, employee, or representative of this policing agency. 

As described in the New York Freedom of Information Law, a record is "any information kept, held, filed, produced or reproduced by, with or for an agency or the state legislature, in any physical form whatsoever including, but not limited to, reports, statements, examinations, memoranda, opinions, folders, files, books, manuals, pamphlets, forms, papers, designs, drawings, maps, photos, letters, microfilms, computer tapes or discs, rules, regulations or codes." Records kept in a digital or electronic form are also records, would be responsive to this request, and should be provided. 

These records are typically required to be retained under the New York State Records Retention and Disposition Schedule MU-1 (http://www.archives.nysed.gov/records/retention_mu-1), including, but not limited to, item no. 365, which includes: "Investigative records and disciplinary proceedings, including but not limited to statement of charge, transcript of hearing, notice of decision, letter of termination or resignation, letter of reinstatement, record of appeal procedure, and correspondence." While materials under that schedule have a set retention of 3 years after the final decision rendered, this request and materials responsive to it include *all* records held in the possession of any office or individual employed or formerly employed by this policing agency, including those kept off-site, in digital form, and in personnel files. 

Please note that any failure to provide all potentially-responsive materials and/or the destruction of materials potentially responsive to this request would be a violation of the spirit of the New York Freedom of Information Law, as well as unlawful under the New York FOIL and the terms of the attached litigation hold notice.

Materials responsive to this request include — but are not limited to — all complaints, reports, records of discipline and penalties, aggregate collections of complaint and disciplinary materials (spreadsheets, databases), investigatory materials, relevant related correspondence, photographs, video, other related evidence, proof of discipline or fulfillment of penalties, and all personnel materials (including those used in promotion, contract, and other employment negotiations and considerations) that reference or utilize misconduct allegations or disciplinary materials of any sort.

Materials responsive to this request include all complaints— internal, external, and civilian — and include records disclosing the names, badge numbers, and personnel identification of each officer involved and/or serving as a witness, as well as all available details of the incident/complaint: date, time, location, nature of the incident, description of the incident, nature of the investigation, investigatory materials, the disposition of the case, and any subsequent materials related to the execution of any resultant discipline. Responsive materials include all complaints and allegations against any officer, employee, or representative of this policing agency, regardless of whether that complaint or allegation resulted in any investigation or disciplinary action. 

Responsive materials also include all records of use of force by officers, including records disclosing the names, badge numbers, and personnel identification of each officer involved and/or serving as a witness, as well as all available details of the incident: date, time, location, nature of the incident, description of the incident, nature of the use of force, subsequent investigatory materials related to the use of force, the disposition of any investigation into the incident, and any subsequent materials related to the use of force. 

Please provide materials on a rolling basis, beginning with materials created during the following timeframes: 
• January 1, 2010 - June 15, 2020
• January 1, 2000 - January 1, 2010
• January 1, 1990 - January 1, 2000
• January 1, 1980 - January 1, 1990
• January 1, 1970 - January 1, 1980

Pursuant to NYCRR Section 1401.5(c)(1), should any of this request be unclear or lack sufficient description for your office, please provide direction that would enable this requester to request records reasonably described. Please also note that the New York FOIL states: "An agency shall not deny a request on the basis that the request is voluminous or that locating or reviewing the requested records or providing the requested copies is burdensome because the agency lacks sufficient staffing or on any other basis if the agency may engage an outside professional service to provide copying, programming or other services required to provide the copy...." Please also see FOIL AO 19671, an Advisory Opinion from the Committee on Open Government [https://docs.dos.ny.gov/coog/ftext/f19671.htm]. 

If your office has questions about this request or would like to discuss it for any reason, please contact this requester via the contact email address provided and feel free to follow up by phone: 617-299-1832. This request is being submitted to each policing agency in New York as part of a collaborative project led by MuckRock and involving multiple other educational and journalistic partners and participants. For this reason, over the lifetime of this request, your agency may interface with individuals not listed on this initial communication. 

This request is being made in the public interest by a news organization as part of non-profit (not commercial) journalistic work and research on behalf of the public. In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request and as part of the necessary negotiations for successful processing. As far as it is possible, please fulfill elements of this request electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter.

I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Beryl Lipton

communications.subject: RE: New York Freedom of Information Law Request: Police department misconduct allegations and disciplinary proceedings
communications.communication:
Hello, Ms. Jones —

I received your email responding to a phone call placed to your office by Hayden Kim to follow up on a FOIL request we submitted in June 2020. 

I have attached the acknowledgement letter sent by your office in April 2021. I would not like to resubmit this request, as we have been patiently waiting for a response for multiple years. I understand that it might take additional weeks to respond to the request at this point, but I would appreciate knowing when your office anticipates being able to release a first batch of records.

Please let me know if you have any questions or would like to discuss this further.

Thank you very much for your time and help. 

Best wishes,
Beryl

communications.communication:
Good afternoon,
We have finally completed the request and downloaded the scanned files to a
disc.  The cost of the disc is $5.00 plus postage totaling *$5.64*.
Unfortunately, we don't have the capabilities to accept payment for FOIL
requests over the phone or website, so it will have to be via check or
money order.  Once we receive payment, I will send the disc in the mail.
Check can be made payable to "City of Fulton" and mailed to 141 S. First St.

                      Fulton, NY 13069
Please reference "Muck Rock FOIL" in the memo line.

Let me know if you have any questions.


Regards,
*Cassandra Jones*
Sr. Account Clerk
City of Fulton Police Department
Phone: 315-598-4504 ext. 3
www.fultonpd.com

communications.subject: Wisconsin Open Records Act Request: David Kahl Interrogation
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Wisconsin Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I would like to request for the interrogation video of  David Kahl, who was interviewed by the  Madison Police Department.
Additionally, I also ask for  Brittany Zimmermann' crime scene reports from April 2, 2008.
and any recordings of 911 calls that are accessible.
as well as any additional case-related investigative materials and photos. Thanks Mahad

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Mahad Mohammed

communications.subject: Re: Thank you for contacting City of Madison Police Records
communications.communication:
Your email request has been received and placed in our processing queue.  Due to the volume of requests, the estimated processing time is as follows:

.         Standard records request (reports/video/photos)- approximately 6-8 weeks

·         Contacts, calls for service or background checks- 2 weeks.


You will be contacted when your request has been completed.

If you are requesting a crash report, these are maintained at the Department of Transportation.  They can be contacted  directly at https://app.wi.gov/crashreports or by calling (608) 266-8753 (and selecting option 3).  For processing this request, you will need the DOT document number located in the upper right corner of the Driver Exchange of Information Form.  This document number will begin with 9B or 01L.  Crash reports are available from DOT approximately 2 weeks after the date of the crash.

If you need any further information, please visit our website at www.cityofmadison.com/police/services<http://www.cityofmadison.com/police/services> or call (608) 266-4075 between 8:00 a.m. and 4:00 p.m. Monday through Friday.  Thank you for contacting Madison Police Records.

communications.communication:

Welcome! Thank you for registering with the City of Madison Public Records Request Center. 
 
Your Login ID is:  182299-95330491@requests.muckrock.com 
 
The Public Records Request Center allows you to:

  * Message the Records Custodian processing your request 
  * Pay online for any fees assessed

communications.subject: INVOICE - Madison Police Department Records Request :: P003801-031825
communications.communication:
RE: Madison Police Department Records Request of March 02, 2025, Reference # 31P003801-031825. 
Dear Mahad Mohammed, 
Your invoice is ready, and available to view. Payment is due within 30 days of the date of the invoice. Payment is required before releasing relevant records. 
Payment options include: 
Online payment:  login to your City of Madison Public Records Request Center account and select View My Invoices. 
You can also pay in-person or by mail at: 
Madison Police Department 
Attn: Police Records 
211 S. Carroll St 
Suite #GR10 
Madison, WI 53703 
 Include the bottom portion of the invoice with your payment. 
 
Sincerely, 
Madison Police Records 
 You must disable your devices pop-up blocker to view your files.  See below for Apple/Android directions. Apple mobile devices default to pop-up blocker ON. To change your settings on your device: Settings-> Apps-> Safari-> Block Pop-ups-> The toggle switch needs to be OFF After making this change, return to the link and attempt to download the document again. Your Apple device will default to opening the item in iBooks unless otherwise specified on your device. Android mobile devices do not have a default pop up blocker but the default browser, Chrome, has a built-in pop-up blocker ON. To turn off the pop-up blocker in Chrome on Android: Open Chrome-> Tap the three dots (more) in the top right corner of the browser-> Settings-> Site Settings- > Pop-ups and redirects-> The toggle switch to allow pop-ups

Android mobile devices do not have a default pop up blocker but the default browser, Chrome, has a built-in pop-up blocker ON. title: Public Records Request - Bedford

communications.subject: Indiana Access to Public Records Act Request: Public Records Request - Bedford
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Indiana Access to Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am writing to formally request access to video footage from a police intervention, specifically from the body camera worn by the officer(s) and the dashcam of the police vehicles involved. Article: https://www.wbiw.com/2025/01/06/bedford-man-arrested-after-disorderly-behavior-and-resisting-arrest-at-local-restaurant/ 

Exact date of incident: December 19, 2024 Names of parties involved: John J. Werner Location: Mammas and Pappas, a local restaurant, Bedford
 
I intend to use this footage solely for educational purposes to promote a better understanding of law enforcement procedures and the application of the law. I understand that there may be associated costs for providing this footage, and I am more than willing to cover any fees incurred. Please inform me about the necessary procedures and the costs involved. Thank you in advance for your assistance. I trust that this footage will be invaluable for my educational efforts, and I greatly appreciate your cooperation. Best regards, George Smith

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

George Smith

title: Public Records Request – Records Pertaining to the Arrest of Ezra Miller on March 28, 2022

communications.subject: Hawaii Uniform Information Practices Act Request: Public Records Request – Records Pertaining to the Arrest of Ezra Miller on March 28, 2022
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Hawaii Uniform Information Practices Act, I hereby request the following records:

I hereby request copies of all records related to the arrest of Ezra Miller on March 28, 2022, in Hilo, Hawaiʻi. This incident involved Mr. Miller allegedly causing a disturbance at a karaoke bar, leading to charges of disorderly conduct and harassment.

Specifically, I request:

1. **Incident and Arrest Reports:**
   - The complete incident report, arrest report, and any supplementary narratives authored by the responding officers concerning this event.
   - Any written statements provided by Mr. Miller during the incident or subsequent arrest process.

2. **Audio and Video Recordings:**
   - All available body-worn camera footage capturing the response, arrest, and any interactions with Mr. Miller.
   - Audio recordings of 911 calls, radio communications, and dispatch logs related to this incident.

3. **Booking and Detention Records:**
   - Mugshot and booking paperwork.
   - Any jail intake forms, property logs, or holding cell surveillance footage (if available).

4. **Internal Communications and Reports:**
   - Internal memos, emails, or communications within the Hawaiʻi Police Department pertaining to this incident.
   - Any reports or assessments generated as a result of this incident, including procedural reviews or evaluations.

I request that these records be provided in electronic format, if available, to facilitate prompt and efficient processing.

**Fee Disclosure and Request for Estimate:**
I acknowledge that this request is being made for commercial purposes. Therefore, I am prepared to incur any applicable fees associated with the processing of this request. To manage costs effectively, I kindly ask that you provide an itemized estimate of the anticipated fees prior to fulfilling the request. If certain documents can be excluded to reduce costs, please inform me so that I can make an informed decision on how to proceed.

If any portion of this request is denied or if specific documents are withheld, please cite the specific statutory exemption that justifies the refusal. Additionally, if certain records are only partially exempt, I request that the non-exempt portions be disclosed after appropriate redaction, as stipulated by the Hawaiʻi Uniform Information Practices Act.

Please confirm receipt of this request and provide an estimated timeline for its fulfillment.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Police Cam News

title: Request for Bodycam Footage – Arrest of Lakenry Roberts on 01/23/2023

communications.subject: Georgia Open Records Act Request: Request for Bodycam Footage – Arrest of Lakenry Roberts on 01/23/2023
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Georgia Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting the body-worn camera footage of the officers who arrested Lakenry B. Roberts. He was taken into custody by the Valdosta Police Department on January 23, 2023, after being found asleep behind the wheel at the intersection of West Magnolia Street and N St. Augustine Road around 2:20 AM. Upon waking him, officers observed signs of impairment and discovered Roberts had a handgun. After a brief conversation, Roberts fled the scene on foot and was apprehended shortly after. He was charged with DUI, possession of a firearm by a convicted felon, obstruction of an officer, suspended license, and open container. I am requesting the available body-worn camera footage from the responding officers who made contact with Roberts, removed the weapon, and took him into custody following the foot pursuit.

Suspect’s Name:
Lakenry B. Roberts

Type of Crime:
DUI, Possession of a Firearm by a Convicted Felon, Obstruction, Suspended License, Open Container

Date of the Arrest:
01/23/2023

Time of the Arrest:
Approximately 2:20 AM

Location of the Arrest:
Intersection of West Magnolia Street and N St. Augustine Road, Valdosta, GA


Arresting Agency: Valdosta Police Department  (booked in Lowndes County jail)

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Christopher Udeani

communications.subject: RE: Oklahoma Open Records Act Request #OCPD-3750-2025
communications.communication:
To whom it may concern: 
I am writing to formally appeal the denial of my request for records under the Oklahoma Open Records Act (“ORA”), which I submitted on 3/26/25. I respectfully request a written explanation detailing the specific grounds for the denial, including the precise subsections of the ORA that are being relied upon.
According to the ORA, “all records of public bodies and public officials shall be open to any person for inspection, copying, or mechanical reproduction during regular business hours…” unless specifically exempted by law. Your response cited the Oklahoma Open Records Act generally, referring to Sections 2, 5, 8, 14, and 20, but did not indicate what specific subsections within those provisions justify withholding the records I requested.
To ensure that the denial complies with the legal requirements of the ORA, and to allow me to properly evaluate the legitimacy of the denial, I ask that you provide the following:
The specific subsection(s) within ORA Sections 2, 5, 8, 14, and/or 20 that are being relied upon.


1. A description of how those subsections apply to the records I requested.


2. A list or description of the categories of records being withheld in whole or in part.


3. Whether any portion of the requested records is non-exempt and therefore subject to partial disclosure with redactions, as required by Oklahoma law.


The law is clear: ORA emphasizes transparency and access to public records as a matter of public policy. The Act requires that denials be specific and justified under the law; vague or categorical denials are inconsistent with both the letter and spirit of the Act.
I respectfully request a response to this appeal within a reasonable timeframe, ideally within seven (7) business days of receipt, so that I may determine my next steps.
If you require any clarification regarding my original request or this appeal, please let me know promptly.
Thank you.

communications.subject: Re: RE: Oklahoma Open Records Act Request #OCPD-3750-2025
communications.communication:

 In order to file an appeal: 
  
 The process is defined in Section 8 of the Open Records Act Law Enforcement Agency Records Available for Public Inspection, a link provided on the JustFOIA web page under “Open Records.” 
  
 Otherwise, the original decision was made by the Municipal Counselors Office. They can be contacted at 405-297-3830. Contact name is Orval Jones. Please provide your request number, OCPD-3750-2025, when you call so that they can reference your request.

In your attached request, we found them to be vague and overbroad as to the documents you are requesting. In an effort to provide you with the specific records that will be most helpful to you, by way of this e-mail, we ask for your assistance in clarifying and narrowing your request.

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: Principal Personnel Files: Suder + Walsh
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

Please supply the full personnel files of the following individuals:

* Bosede Bada, Principal
* Araceli Ibarra, Principal

This includes any resumes, applications, any job recommendations, promotions, professional license credentials and verification records. Please include a work/salary history. Please include any investigative materials - investigative memorandums, disciplinary actions (suspensions, leaves of absence that stem from disciplinary action), EOCO investigations, Office of Civil Rights determinations, non-disciplinary memorandum of understandings, non-union misconduct form, full warning resolutions and any complaints or claims/lawsuits/settlements/agreements. Please include any safety plans. Please include any separation agreements and any other disclosure agreements.

This request is on behalf of The FOIA Bakery, an Illinois nonprofit. Because this request is in the public interest for Illinois nonprofit The FOIA Bakery’s work to advocate for public education, please waive any fees in accordance with 5 ILCS § 140/6(c). Feel free to contact me with any questions, or if clarification is needed.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Miriam Bhimani

Chicago Public Schools (CPS) responds to all public records requests in accordance with the Illinois Freedom of Information Act (FOIA), 5 ILCS 140/1 et seq. 
Due to the volume and complexity of requests received in the normal course of business, CPS is extending the time for its initial response to your request by an additional 5 business days (to 10 business days total beginning on the first business day following receipt of the request) pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/3(e)(v) which allows for the examination and evaluation of the requested records by personnel to determine if they are exempt from disclosure under Section 7 of Illinois FOIA or should be revealed only with appropriate deletions. 
Upon the completion of a response, CPS will provide the first 50 pages to you at no charge.  If a response is more than 50 pages, a fee of 15¢ per page will be charged for each additional page. All applicable fees must be paid prior to the copying. CPS will inform you of any fees due if your paper response exceeds 50 pages. communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 
July 7, 2025 Miriam Bhimani RE: Chicago Public Schools FOIA Request N017793-061925 Dear Miriam Bhimani: This letter is in reply to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) Request seeking the following information: 
Please supply the full personnel files of the following individuals: 
* Bosede Bada, Principal 
* Araceli Ibarra, Principal 
This includes any resumes, applications, any job recommendations, promotions, professional license credentials and verification records. Please include a work/salary history. Please include any investigative materials - investigative memorandums, disciplinary actions (suspensions, leaves of absence that stem from disciplinary action), EOCO investigations, Office of Civil Rights determinations, non-disciplinary memorandum of understandings, non-union misconduct form, full warning resolutions and any complaints or claims/lawsuits/settlements/agreements. Please include any safety plans. Please include any separation agreements and any other disclosure agreements. RESPONSE : Documents responsive to your FOIA request are available to download via the Chicago Public Schools FOIA Center. Please visit the following link and enter your username and password to access the records: http://cps.edu/About_CPS/Departments/Law/Pages/FOIARequest.aspx . Pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7 (1)(b), “Private information, unless disclosure is required by another provision of this Act, a State or federal law or a court order,” and pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(c), “Personal information contained within public records, the disclosure of which would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy, unless the disclosure is consented to in writing by the individual subjects of the information. “Unwarranted invasion of personal privacy” means the disclosure of information that is highly personal or objectionable to a reasonable person and in which the subject’s right to privacy outweighs the legitimate public interest in obtaining the information. The disclosure of information that bears on the public duties of public employees and officials shall not be considered an invasion of personal privacy. Redactions have been made pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(a) corresponding with 105 ILCS 5/34-18.5(b) which prohibits the release of background check information. Furthermore, Illinois state law prohibits the release of portions of public employee personnel files, such as teacher performance evaluations. Per 105 ILCS 5/24A-7.1, “Disclosure of public school teacher, principal, and superintendent performance evaluations is prohibited,” and 820 ILCS 40/11, “Disclosure of performance evaluations under the Freedom of Information Act shall be prohibited,” and related documents have been removed. Portions of the information you seek is exempt from disclosure pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7 (1)(f) exempts any “Preliminary drafts, notes, recommendations, memoranda and other records in which opinions are expressed, or policies or actions are formulated, except that a specific record or relevant portion of a record shall not be exempt when the record is publicly cited and identified by the head of the public body.” Redactions have been made pursuant to Section 7(1)(d)(iv) which allows a public to withhold records/information that would unavoidably reveal the identity of a complainant or witness. Records of discipline more than four years old are exempt from disclosure pursuant to section 7.5(q) of the FOIA (5 ILCS 140/7.5(q)), which exempts information prohibited from being disclosed by the Personnel Records Review Act [820 ILCS 40/0.01 et seq.]. 820 ILCS 40/8 of the Personnel Records Review Act states that “an employer shall review a personnel record before releasing information to a third party and, except when the release is ordered to a party in a legal action or arbitration, delete disciplinary reports, letters of reprimand, or other records of disciplinary action which are more than 4 years old.” Safety plans, if any, are exempt from disclosure pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(v):Vulnerability assessments, security measures, and response policies or plans that are designed to identify, prevent, or respond to potential attacks upon a community’s population or systems, facilities, or installations, the destruction or contamination of which would constitute a clear and present danger to the health or safety of the community, but only to the extent that disclosure could reasonably be expected to jeopardize the effectiveness of the measures or the safety of the personnel who implement them or the public. Information exempt under this item may include such things as details pertaining to the mobilization or deployment of personnel or equipment, to the operations of communication systems or protocols, or to tactical operations. Records have been withheld pursuant to Section 7.5(h) of the FOIA, which exempts from disclosure “information the disclosure of which is exempted under the State Officials and Employees Ethics Act, and records of any lawfully created State or local inspector general’s office that would be exempt if created or obtained by an Executive Inspector General’s office.” 5 ILCS 140/7.5(h). To the extent you consider this a denial, you have a right to have your request reviewed by the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at the Office of the Illinois Attorney General pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a). You can file your Request for Review with the PAC by writing to: Public Access Counselor Office of the Attorney General 500 South 2nd Street Springfield, Illinois 62706 Fax: 217-782-1396 E-mail: publicaccess@atg.state.il.us You also have the right to seek judicial review of your denial by filing a lawsuit in the State circuit court pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/11. Thank you. Sincerely, Ana Diaz Freedom of Information Act Officer Chicago Public Schools

07/07/2025 
Miriam Bhimani 
Dear Miriam Bhimani: 
RE: Chicago Public Schools FOIA Request N017792-061925 
The CPS FOIA Office has reviewed your request and has determined the following: 
N017791-061925 - "...1. A log of all emails to/from the Kishasha Williams-Ford from May 16, 2025 - May 20, 2025. Please search all CPS email accounts as well as personal accounts used for public business. The log should include but not be limited to: sender, recipient(s), date and time, subject line, and attachment. 2. A log of all phone calls and messages for Kishasha Williams-Ford from May 16, 2025 - May 20, 2025..." N017792-061925 - "...1. A log of all emails to/from the Kishasha Williams-Ford from May 21, 2025 - May 25, 2025. Please search all CPS email accounts as well as personal accounts used for public business. The log should include but not be limited to: sender, recipient(s), date and time, subject line, and attachment. 2. A log of all phone calls and messages for Kishasha Williams-Ford from May 21, 2025 - May 25, 2025..." RESPONSE: Documents responsive to your request are available to download via the CPS FOIA Center at www.cps.edu/FOIARequests . Please log in with your username and password to access the records. Please be advised that because there are over 2,100 lines of emails required for individual review from May 16, 2025 through May 25, 2025, in lieu of burdening this part of your request, recipient metadata has been excluded from this production because of the custodian's role which involves communications from parents exempt under section 7.5(r) and complaints received relating to LSC matters which are exempt pursuant to s ection 7(d)(iv) of the FOIA. Should you wish to request certain email lines with recipient data, please provide a list of the control numbers. Please note that certain private information (personal phone numbers, etc.) was redacted pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7. Specifically, section 7(1)(b) which exempts certain private information as defined by section 2(c-5) and section 7(1)(c) which exempts personal information contained within public records, the disclosure of which would constitute a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy, unless the disclosure is consented to in writing by the individual subject of the information. “Unwarranted invasion of personal privacy” means the disclosure of information that is highly personal or objectionable to a reasonable person and in which the subject’s right to privacy outweighs any legitimate public interest in obtaining the information. Section 7.5(h) exempts from disclosure “information the disclosure of which is exempted under the State Officials and Employees Ethics Act, and records of any lawfully created State or local inspector general’s office that would be exempt if created or obtained by an Executive Inspector General’s office.” 5 ILCS 140/7.5(h). Student information has been redacted pursuant to 5 ILCS 140/7.5 (r) which exempts from inspection or copying information prohibited from being disclosed by the Illinois School Student Records Act (ISSRA). ISSRA generally prohibits the disclosure of “school student records” and defines a “school student record” as “any writing or other recorded information concerning a student and by which a student may be individually identified, maintained by a school or at is direction or by an employee of a school, regardless of how or where the information is stored.” (105 ILCS 10/2(d). Section 7(d)(iv) of the FOIA exempts confidential information furnished only by the confidential source, or persons who file complaints with or provide information to administrative, investigative, law enforcement, or penal agencies. You have a right to have the denial of your request reviewed by the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at the Office of the Illinois Attorney General. 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a). You can file your Request for Review with the PAC by writing to: Leah Bartelt; Public Access Counselor Office of the Attorney General 500 South 2nd Street Springfield, Illinois 62706 E-mail: public.access@ilag.gov 877-299-3642 You also have the right to seek judicial review of your denial by filing a lawsuit in the State circuit court. 5 ILCS 140/11. If you choose to file a Request for Review with the PAC, you must do so within 60 calendar days of the date of this denial letter. 5 ILCS 140/9.5(a). Please note that you must include a copy of your original FOIA request and this denial letter when filing a Request for Review with the PAC. Sincerely, Patricia Majchrowicz Freedom of Information Act Officer Chicago Public Schools

title: Civil Commitment Data and Demographic Breakdown for Illinois (Department of Human Services)

communications.subject: Illinois Freedom of Information Act. Request: Civil Commitment Data and Demographic Breakdown for Illinois (Department of Human Services)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Illinois Freedom of Information Act., I hereby request the following records:

Total number of individuals civilly committed in Illinois for the most recent calendar year (2024), or the latest year for which data is available. 
Demographic breakdown of the civilly committed by:
Disability status (e.g., mental illness, intellectual disability, etc.)
Race
Gender
Housing status at the time of commitment (e.g., stably housed, homeless, in transitional housing)
Citizenship status (e.g., U.S. citizen, non citizen)
Region of commitment (please breakdown by city, county, and/or state region, if available)
If at all possible, please provide both numerical counts and percentages for each subcategory. 
Please provide this information in electronic format (PDF, Excel or CSV preferred). If records are only partially available or some data fields cannot be broken down as requested, I ask that any available portions still be provided. If any part of this request is unclear, I welcome clarification to ensure that it is processed efficiently.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Center for Racial and Disability Justice

communications.subject: 25-FTS-7809 MuckRock- EXTENSION REQUEST
communications.communication:
Dear MuckRock:

The Illinois Department of Human Services received your Freedom of Information Act request on June 20, 2025.  You requested the following information:


Total number of individuals civilly committed in Illinois for the most recent calendar year (2024), or the latest year for which data is available.
Demographic breakdown of the civilly committed by:
Disability status (e.g., mental illness, intellectual disability, etc.)
Race
Gender
Housing status at the time of commitment (e.g., stably housed, homeless, in transitional housing)
Citizenship status (e.g., U.S. citizen, non citizen)
Region of commitment (please breakdown by city, county, and/or state region, if available)
If at all possible, please provide both numerical counts and percentages for each subcategory.
Please provide this information in electronic format (PDF, Excel or CSV preferred). If records are only partially available or some data fields cannot be broken down as requested, I ask that any available portions still be provided. If any part of this request is unclear, I welcome clarification to ensure that it is processed efficiently.

The Department is still processing your request.  Under the Freedom of Information Act, a public body may extend the time to respond to a FOIA request by up to five business days. 5 ILCS 140/3(e).    As such, the Department is extending the time to respond to your request by five business days on one or more of the following bases:



•          The requested records are stored in whole or in part at other locations than the office having charge of the requested records;

•          The request requires the collection of a substantial number of specified records;

communications.subject: 25-FTS-7809 MuckRock - RESPONSE
communications.communication:
Dear MuckRock:

The Illinois Department of Human Services received your Freedom of Information Act request on June 20, 2025.  You requested the following information:

Total number of individuals civilly committed in Illinois for the most recent calendar year (2024), or the latest year for which data is available.
Demographic breakdown of the civilly committed by:
Disability status (e.g., mental illness, intellectual disability, etc.)
Race
Gender
Housing status at the time of commitment (e.g., stably housed, homeless, in transitional housing)
Citizenship status (e.g., U.S. citizen, non citizen)
Region of commitment (please breakdown by city, county, and/or state region, if available)
If at all possible, please provide both numerical counts and percentages for each subcategory.
Please provide this information in electronic format (PDF, Excel or CSV preferred). If records are only partially available or some data fields cannot be broken down as requested, I ask that any available portions still be provided. If any part of this request is unclear, I welcome clarification to ensure that it is processed efficiently.
Attached is information responsive to your request.

Please note that the Department withheld citizenship status pursuant to Section 7(1)(b) of FOIA, which applies to private information. 5 ILCS 140/7(1)(b); 5 ILCS 140/2(c-5).

To the extent you consider any portion of this response to be an improper denial of your FOIA request, you have a right to seek review by writing to the Public Access Counselor (PAC) at the following address:

title: Flock Safety search audits, network sharing, and general order (Medina Police Department)

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Flock Safety search audits, network sharing, and general order (Medina Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records related to the department’s Flock Safety system:
1. Organization Audit in Flock. 
The report should include data logged from the period of December 1, 2024, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Organization Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches done within the agency.

2. Network Audit in Flock.
The report should include data logged from the period of December 1, 2024, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Network Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches of the organization’s Flock network by any agency in the Flock System.

3. A list of network share settings that include:
3a. Flock networks shared with me
3b. Networks that I’m sharing

Please provide records in their original electronic, machine readable format. For example, please provide csv or spreadsheet files where applicable. Please do not redirect me to your transparency portal.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Rose Terse

--- Please respond above this line --- 
This email shall acknowledge receipt of your Freedom of Information Law (“FOIL”) request, directed to the MTA. 

This is to advise you that we are in the process of reviewing our files for the records you requested and anticipate being able to furnish you with your response on or before 8/30/2024.  Access to any record requested will be determined in accordance with the Public Officers Law. 

Please be advised that the MTA FOIL Unit receives a high volume of FOIL requests ranging from simple to complex requests and all documents and records require review prior to disclosure. As a result, documents and records will not be immediately available. Under certain circumstances of the request, such as, the number of documents requested, their format, their availability, the time it takes to review and redact any information that cannot be disclosed pursuant to FOIL, the time it takes to assemble the documents, and other factors, processing and response times may be delayed. Since the time and effort required to complete a response can vary significantly, the MTA endeavors to complete each request in a time period that is reasonable under the circumstances of the request. 

Regards, 
MTA FOIL Team

communications.subject: RE: Virginia Freedom of Information Act Request #25-96
communications.communication:
Thank you for sending what appears to be a PARTIAL response to my FOIA.  Per my original FOIA request, the records appear to be MISSING the following records:

1. REQUESTED: Copies of the AY 2024 - 2025 DEI/DOI/Inclusive Excellence Facilitators Guide for Cadet and Faculty Training.

MISSING - Neither the Cadet nor the Faculty Facilitator's Guides were provided. If FOIA's on your site show that versions of these existed for previous years and were disclosed. I am asking for the current version for AY 2024 - 2025 - PLEASE PROVIDE THEM.

2. Copies of the Instructor notes and slides (with links to any videos used) for each of the AY 2024-2025 DEI/DOI/Inclusive Excellence Facilitators' Guide for Cadet and Faculty Training.

MISSING - No instructor notes and slides provided for FIRST CLASS (Seniors) training. VMI documentation indicates that this "training" may take the form of a guest speaker or lecture, but it should exist as VMI stated it does for all classes.

MISSING - All instructor notes and slides for VMI Faculty and Staff training that VMI states it conducts.

3. Copies of the Instructor notes and slides (with links to any videos used) for each of the AY 2024-2025 DEI/DOI/Inclusive Excellence Facilitators' Guide for Board of Visitors Training.

MISSING - None of these records were provided, although VMI Quarterly and other reports and publications state that this training is required and conducted annually for the BOV.

Thank you in advance for providing this missing information. Whereas VMI Committed and reported to the Commonwealth, and publicly posted, it is conducting this training, these records must be available unless VMI is non-compliant.

title: Request to State Department for all communications with film director Doug Liman

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Request to State Department for all communications with film director Doug Liman
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any communications between the State Department or employees thereof and the Hollywood film director Doug Liman, born Douglas Eric Liman on July 24, 1965. Such communications may include, but should not be limited to, emails, correspondence, memos, and transcriptions of telephone calls. 

I am the Director of Research Operations at a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization called The Decoding Culture Foundation. These documents will be used for public education and research purposes. I therefore request a waiver of all fees that may otherwise apply. Attached is a document with organization letterhead confirming my position, as well as the organization's 501(c)(3) application and approval form.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brett Carollo

title: GPS at Massachusetts Sheriffs Offices (Essex County Sheriff)

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: GPS at Massachusetts Sheriffs Offices (Essex County Sheriff)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Massachusetts Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

Records that detail the extent of your office's usage of GPS technology to monitor people in the Sheriff office's custody. This includes individuals under pretrial, sentenced, on SORB, or any other custodial status. If such a program exists, I request records that show the number of individuals currently on GPS monitors, and their status (ie pretrial, sentenced, etc).

I also request that, if appropriate, fees be waived as we believe this request is in the public interest, as suggested but not stipulated by the recommendations of the Massachusetts Supervisor of Public Records. The requested documents will be made available to the general public free of charge as part of the public information service at MuckRock.com, and is not made for commercial usage.

I expect the request to be filled in an accessible format, including for screen readers, which provide text-to-speech for persons unable to read print. Files that are not accessible to screen readers include, for example, .pdf image files as well as physical documents.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Joshua Dankoff

communications.subject: RE: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: GPS at Massachusetts Sheriffs Offices (Essex County Sheriff)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Thanks for your help, and let me know if further clarification is needed.

communications.subject: Massachusetts Public Records Law Request: GPS at Massachusetts Sheriffs Offices (Essex County Sheriff)
communications.communication:
Good afternoon,

I am writing in response to your public records request, dated June 12, 2025, directed to the Essex County Sheriff's Department. I serve as Assistant General Counsel to the Department.  As you know, your request specifically sought "[r]ecords that detail the extent of your office's usage of GPS technology to monitor people in the Sheriff's office's custody. This includes individuals under pretrial, sentences, on SORB, or any other custodial status. If such a program exists, I request records that show the number of individuals currently on GPS monitors, and their status."

As you may know, the Essex County Sheriff's Department has multiple facilities - the Middleton House of Correction in Middleton, MA, the Essex County Pre-Release and Re-Entry Center ("ECPRC") in Lawrence, MA, and the Women in Transition ("WIT") facility in Salisbury, MA. I am advised by Department officials that every inmate at the ECPRC, both sentenced and pretrial inmates, has a GPS monitoring device. The Department reserves the right to place a GPS monitoring device on a sentenced inmate at the WIT if the Department deems it necessary.

While you requested data on the number of inmates with GPS monitoring, the overall number fluctuates daily due to new intakes, releases, etc. As of June 23, 2025, the total number was 100 - the breakdown was 92 sentenced and 8 pretrial. There are also 3 sentenced inmates who have GPS monitoring but are not in the Department's direct custody.

Thank you,

Jordan Elizabeth Mitchell
Assistant General Counsel
Essex County Sheriff's Department
20 Manning Avenue
Middleton, MA 01949

title: FBI support for National Geographic TV series "Trafficked with Mariana Van Zeller"

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FBI support for National Geographic TV series "Trafficked with Mariana Van Zeller"
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any documents pertaining to FBI support for or collaboration with the production of National Geographic Channel TV series "Trafficked with Mariana Van Zeller," between 2019 and 2023. Such documents may include, but are not limited to, script notes; production assistance agreements; and all records of communications between employees of the FBI and members of the cast, crew, and production company of "Trafficked with Mariana Van Zeller," including memos, notes of meetings and conference calls, emails, and other forms of communication.I request a search of all locations where such documents might be located, including but not limited to the entertainment liaison offices and communications HQ or similar offices.

Attached is a document, released to me by the FBI, confirming that, some time between 2019 and 2023, the FBI supported the production of this series. 

I am the Director of Research Operations at a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization called The Decoding Culture Foundation. These documents will be used for public education and research purposes. I therefore request a waiver of all fees that may otherwise apply. Attached is a document with organization letterhead confirming my position, as well as the organization's 501(c)(3) application and approval form.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brett Carollo

communications.subject: RE: [EXTERNAL EMAIL] -  RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1628230-000
communications.communication:
Thank you for contacting foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

Please check the status of your FOIPA Request at http://vault.fbi.gov by clicking on “Check Status of Your FOI/PA Request” on the right side of the page, and follow the instructions below.

Check the Status of Your FOIPA Request

If your FOIPA Number is [1195846-0] please enter [1195846-000] into the system. If your FOIPA Number is [1195846-1] please enter [1195846-001] into the system. If you have any questions about the status of your FOIPA request, please e-mail foipaquestions@fbi.gov.

FIND STATUS OF FOIPA- Request statuses are updated weekly

Please enter the whole FOIPA number-Example: [1234567-000]

FOIPA:
Results will show the Request Number, Case Type and Process Description shown below:
FOIPA:
1234567-000
Case Type:
FOIPA
Process Description (Will display the current progress of the request)

The FBI’s FOIPA Program is searching the FBI’s indices for potentially responsive documents.

You may be contacted via formal letter for all fees and/or negotiation issues that may apply.

NOTE: Recent requests are entered into the FOIPA database in the order that they are received. Before you can check the status, you must have received correspondence assigning a FOIPA request number and the information transferred to the online database. Status information is updated weekly. If a request has been closed within the last six months the online database will display the following: The FOIPA number entered has been closed, and appropriate correspondence has been sent to the address on file.


Estimated Dates of Completion
Requests are processed in the order in which they are received through our multi-track processing system, and the FBI receives a voluminous amount of requests on a daily, weekly, monthly, and annual basis.  Requests are divided into two primary tracks--simple (under 50 pages of potentially responsive documents) and complex (over 50 pages of potentially responsive documents).  Our complex requests are further divided into small (51-250 pages), medium (251-500 pages), large (501-4,999), and extra-large (over 5,000 pages) sub-tracks.  Simple track requests typically require the least amount of time to process.  The more potentially responsive pages a request has, the more complex it becomes, greatly increasing the time required for processing. Generally, the larger the file, the longer it takes to process.
Currently, simple track cases average approximately 230 days from the date of receipt for processing.  Complex requests in the small processing track are currently averaging 1,085 days from the date of receipt for processing, those in the medium processing track are currently averaging 1,310 days, those in the large processing track are currently averaging approximately 2,010 days, and those in the extra-large track are averaging 2,370 days  .


Respectfully,


Public Information Officer
FBI - Information Management Division
200 Constitution Drive
Winchester, VA  22602
O: (540) 868-4593
E: foipaquestions@fbi.gov<mailto:foipaquestions@fbi.gov>

Do you have further questions about the FOI/PA process? Visit us at http://www.fbi.gov/foia

Please check the status of your request online at https://vault.fbi.gov/fdps-1/@@search-fdps    Status updates are performed on a weekly basis.

Note:  This is a non-emergency email address.  If this is an emergency, please call 911 directly.  If you need to report a tip for immediate action, please contact FBI Tips at http://tips.fbi.gov/ or reach out to your local field office.

communications.subject: RE: Freedom of Information Act Request #1628230-000
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern

I am writing to appeal the decision to deny waiver of fees for request #1628230-000.

According to your determination, my request did not meet the standard for waiver of fees because it would be unlikely to contribute significantly to the public's understanding of government operations.

As I explain in my original FOIA request, I am the Director of Research Operations at a non-profit organization that makes these records available to the public. These and other records thus made available will, we hope and expect, be referenced in research papers and other writings, and the mere availability of them makes the public aware of an entire field of government operations (namely, collaboration with Hollywood) of which the public is largely not aware. This increased awareness, in turn, has the potential to transform the way the public sees films. Furthermore, I am the editor-in-chief of a research magazine published by said foundation  called "Cultural Engineering Studies," to which I also contribute articles (including a recent article on NASA's relationship to Hollywood). The magazine explores, among other topics, Hollywood's relationship to the federal government, and such documents indeed are cited in the magazine.

I therefore repeat my request for a waiver of fees, having rebutted the finding that this work does not contribute in any significant way to the public's understanding of government. 

In the event that this waiver request is not accepted, I still wish you to process the FOIA request, under the stipulations stated in the original request.

Sincerely,

Brett Carollo

communications.subject: Colorado Open Records Act Request: CO County CVR Request (Boulder County Clerk & Recorder Offices)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Colorado Open Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Cast vote record (CVR) data for the following elections:
1. 2022 Nov Midterm Election
2. 2024 Nov General Election

Specifically, I’m looking for the full anonymized record of votes cast each election generated by the voting system.

In case it is helpful for your reference, you can find an example of these records in REDACTED format at this link on the Arapahoe County webpage: https://www.arapahoevotes.gov/transparency
If you follow the "Redacted Cast Vote Record (CVR)" link on that webpage, it will download a csv file with Arapahoe County's redacted CVR records (this: https://gis.arapahoegov.com/dl_data/cr_voter_data/redacted_cvr/REDACTED_CVR_Export_20241126111830_330948.zip.)

I am requesting these records NOT redacted pursuant to the Colorado Open Records Act. Please let me know if you need any further clarification on the type of data that I am requesting.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 3 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Aleksandra Conevska

communications.subject: Re: [EXTERNAL] Colorado Open Records Act Request: CO County CVR Request (Boulder County Clerk & Recorder Offices)
communications.communication:
Hi Aleksandra -

Our redacted 2024 General election CVR is already posted to our website here: https://bouldercounty.gov/elections/results/

Information on submitting a request for the 2022 CVR can be found here: https://bouldercounty.gov/records/colorado-open-records-act/

We do not release unredacted CVRs due to the statutory requirements around protecting voter anonymity.

Stephanie

I also kindly request answers to the following questions related to the compensation study:

For the faculty database, I am requesting the following information:

Additionally, copies of the following documents, if available:

Employee Benefit Information (Holidays Off, Health Insurance, Etc)
Salary Adjustment Policy (Longevity, performance, COLA, etc)
Any Collective Bargaining Agreements
Current Turnover Rate
Current Average Tenure
Date that your current pay plan was implemented
Date of your last salary adjustment to pay plan
How frequently are your job descriptions updated
Do you have a planned salary adjustment to your compensation structures for the next fiscal year? If so, by what amount?
Please list/attach and supplements/additives that faculty are compensated for duties outside of instruction
Faculty Handbooks
Adjunct Rates/Pay Plan
Overload Rates
Rates for compensation for faculty leadership- Deans, Coordinators, Department Chairs
Do you compensate faculty differently based on area of discipline? If yes, please provide details.
Do you have any form of additional compensation for Large Class Size? If yes, please provide details.
Do you have an education incentive at your institution? If yes, please provide details.

I understand that public records requests may involve administrative processes and associated fees, as allowed by law. Please inform me of any fees and the estimated timeframe for fulfilling this request. If any portion of this request is denied, please provide a written explanation for the denial, citing the specific legal grounds for the refusal.

Alisia Rios
